{
  "texts": [
    "As expected, hub distributions had similar patterns between replicates, that is, adjacent sections of tumor tissues (for example, P1A_ER, P1B_ER), whereas hubs dominated by tumor cells were different between patients (for example, P1, P2) (Fig. 3j, k).",
    "By integrating ST datasets, we systematically compared tumor heterogeneity and its interplay with tumor-immune characteristics across breast cancer subtypes.",
    "In particular, we investigated potential differences in cellular organization in MBC compared to other TNBCs 50.",
    "MBC is a rare and aggressive form making up 1-2% of all breast cancer 40 and typically characterized as TNBC due to lack of expression of ER, progesterone receptor (PR) and human epidermal growth factor 2 receptor (HER2).",
    "However, MBCs have worse prognosis and greater resistance to chemotherapy than conventional TNBC 40, 51, 52."
  ]
}